{"created-date": {"value": 1690447880146}, "last-modified-date": {"value": 1690447880146}, "source": {"source-orcid": {"uri": "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-9785-7726", "path": "0000-0002-9785-7726", "host": "orcid.org"}, "source-client-id": null, "source-name": {"value": "Luca Baldini"}, "assertion-origin-orcid": null, "assertion-origin-client-id": null, "assertion-origin-name": null}, "put-code": 139395214, "path": "/0000-0002-9785-7726/work/139395214", "title": {"title": {"value": "X-Ray Polarimetry of the Accreting Pulsar 1A 0535+262 in the Supercritical State with PolarLight"}, "subtitle": null, "translated-title": null}, "journal-title": {"value": "The Astrophysical Journal"}, "short-description": "<jats:title>Abstract</jats:title>\n               <jats:p>The X-ray pulsar 1A 0535+262 exhibited a giant outburst in 2020, offering us a unique opportunity for X-ray polarimetry of an accreting pulsar in the supercritical state. Measurement with PolarLight yielded a nondetection in 3\u20138 keV; the 99% upper limit of the polarization fraction (PF) is found to be 0.34 averaged over spin phases, or 0.51 based on the rotating vector model. No useful constraint can be placed with phase-resolved polarimetry. These upper limits are lower than a previous theoretical prediction of 0.6\u20130.8, but consistent with those found in other accreting pulsars, like Her X-1, Cen X-3, 4U 1626\u221267, and GRO J1008\u221257, which were in the subcritical state, or at least not confidently in the supercritical state, during the polarization measurements. Our results suggest that the relatively low PF seen in accreting pulsars cannot be attributed to the source not being in the supercritical state, but could be a general feature.</jats:p>", "citation": {"citation-type": "bibtex", "citation-value": "@article{Long_2023,\tdoi = {10.3847/1538-4357/acd0af},\turl = {https://doi.org/10.3847%2F1538-4357%2Facd0af},\tyear = 2023,\tmonth = {jun},\tpublisher = {American Astronomical Society},\tvolu